🟢 1️⃣ Definition

Decorator Pattern allows you to add new behavior to an object dynamically without modifying its class.

🎯 Core Idea
Instead of:
Changing class ❌

Do:
Wrap object → add behavior ✅
🧠 2️⃣ Real-Life Analogy
☕ Coffee Shop

Base coffee:

Simple Coffee

Add-ons:

+ Milk
+ Sugar
+ Whipped Cream

👉 You don’t create:

MilkCoffee
SugarCoffee
MilkSugarCoffee

❌ That would explode into too many classes

👉 Instead:

Wrap coffee with add-ons dynamically ✅
🔥 3️⃣ Problem It Solves
❌ Without Decorator (Inheritance explosion)
Coffee
 ├── MilkCoffee
 ├── SugarCoffee
 ├── MilkSugarCoffee
 ├── MilkSugarCreamCoffee

👉 Too many combinations ❌

✅ 4️⃣ Decorator Solution

👉 Use composition instead of inheritance

🧱 5️⃣ Structure
1️⃣ Component Interface
interface Coffee {
    int cost();
}
2️⃣ Concrete Component
class SimpleCoffee implements Coffee {
    public int cost() {
        return 10;
    }
}
3️⃣ Base Decorator
abstract class CoffeeDecorator implements Coffee {

    protected Coffee coffee;

    public CoffeeDecorator(Coffee coffee) {
        this.coffee = coffee;
    }
}
4️⃣ Concrete Decorators
Milk
class MilkDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {

    public MilkDecorator(Coffee coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    public int cost() {
        return coffee.cost() + 5;
    }
}
Sugar
class SugarDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {

    public SugarDecorator(Coffee coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    public int cost() {
        return coffee.cost() + 3;
    }
}
5️⃣ Usage
Coffee coffee = new SimpleCoffee();

coffee = new MilkDecorator(coffee);
coffee = new SugarDecorator(coffee);

System.out.println(coffee.cost()); // 10 + 5 + 3 = 18
🔥 What Happened?
SimpleCoffee
    ↓ wrapped by Milk
    ↓ wrapped by Sugar

👉 Each decorator adds behavior

🧠 6️⃣ Step-by-Step Flow
1. Create base object
2. Wrap with decorator
3. Each decorator adds functionality
4. Final result accumulates behavior
🎯 Key Insight

Decorator wraps the object and adds behavior before/after delegating to it

